messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /profiles/{id}

All methods acceptable:
- false

Method availability for the endpoint /profiles/{id} (based on the code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation:
- index.js mounts the router with app.use('/profiles', profile). That makes the router paths under the prefix /profiles.
- routes/profile.js maps router.delete('/:id', deleteProfile) to the controller deleteProfile. Combined with the prefix, that yields /profiles/:id, represented here as /profiles/{id}.
- The same router also defines router.get('/:id', getProfile) and router.patch('/:id', updateProfile), so GET and PATCH are explicitly allowed on /profiles/{id}. DELETE is explicitly allowed (deleteProfile).
- POST is only registered at router.post('/') (i.e., /profiles), not at /profiles/:id, so POST is not allowed on /profiles/{id}.
- There is no router.put, router.options, router.trace, or router.head in the code, and there is no router.all or app.all registering every method; therefore PUT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and HEAD are not explicitly acceptable per the source code.
- Per your instruction, I judged availability only from explicit route registrations in the code (no assumptions about Express implicit HEAD handling).
